# gen142 (E8) STRESS: ~10x the minimal case. All five epistemic states, each with
# DIFFERENT grounded confidence language, plus the "why?" and "what would change
# your mind?" follow-ups, interleaved across many held-out nonsense predicates so
# nothing can pass by memorizing a phrase. The confidence is COMPUTED from the
# real proof state every turn: rule chains, direct facts, closed-world absence,
# self-contradiction, and standing suppositions. The hardest case is COMPOSITIONAL
# — a HYPOTHETICAL assumption feeding a RULE: the derived conclusion is still
# graded conditional because ablation finds it rests on the assumed fact.

# INFERRED — one-step rule. Confidence cites the chain; lever is the premise.
> zeppo is a quux
< Learned: quux(zeppo).
> every quux is a blorp
< Learned rule: blorp(X) :- quux(X).
> is zeppo a blorp?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< I'm confident but it's derived, not given: blorp(zeppo) because quux(zeppo). I concluded it by applying a rule, so it's only as sound as those premises.
> what would make you change your mind?
< It hangs on one premise: if I learned that zeppo is a quux were false, I'd stop concluding zeppo is a blorp.

# KNOWN — direct fact, then the state SWITCHES (it must re-grade, not stick).
> glim is a frob
< Learned: frob(glim).
> is glim a frob?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< I'm certain: glim is a frob is a fact you stated directly, so I hold it as known, not inferred.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Learning that glim is NOT a frob — that's the single fact it rests on, so contradicting it would overturn my belief.

# UNKNOWN — known predicate, unknown entity. Honest absence either way.
> is wibol a frob?
< No.
> why do you think that?
< I don't actually think that — I have no support for wibol being a frob, so I can't claim it either way.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Learning whether wibol is a frob at all — right now I have no support either way, so any fact about it would be new ground.

# CONFLICTED — both polarities. Genuinely unsure; both claims named both ways.
> snarf is a dax
< Learned: dax(snarf).
> snarf is not a dax
< Learned: not dax(snarf).
> is snarf a dax?
< No.
> why do you think that?
< I'm genuinely unsure — I hold conflicting claims about snarf: you told me it is a dax and also that it is not. Until that's resolved I can't commit either way.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Telling me which to trust — you've claimed both that snarf is a dax and that it is not. Retract one and I'd settle on the other.

# HYPOTHETICAL feeding a RULE — composition. The conclusion is DERIVED, yet still
# graded conditional because it rests on the standing assumption (found by
# ablation through the rule).
> suppose krill is a vorp
< All right — assuming krill is a vorp. Anything I conclude from it will be conditional on that.
> every vorp is a zonk
< Learned rule: zonk(X) :- vorp(X).
> is krill a zonk?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< Only conditionally: krill is a zonk holds because I'm ASSUMING krill is a vorp. Drop that assumption and I'd have no ground for it.
> what would make you change your mind?
< Dropping the assumption — I only conclude krill is a zonk because I'm supposing krill is a vorp. Withdraw that and the conclusion goes with it.

# DEEP chain — the lever stays grounded in the single root premise across two
# rule hops, then the state switches back to KNOWN on a fresh goal.
> figo is a alpha
< Learned: alpha(figo).
> every alpha is a beta
< Learned rule: beta(X) :- alpha(X).
> every beta is a gamma
< Learned rule: gamma(X) :- beta(X).
> is figo a gamma?
< Yes.
> what would make you change your mind?
< It hangs on one premise: if I learned that figo is a alpha were false, I'd stop concluding figo is a gamma.
> pim is a wug
< Learned: wug(pim).
> is pim a wug?
< Yes.
> why do you think that?
< I'm certain: pim is a wug is a fact you stated directly, so I hold it as known, not inferred.
